SIMPLE: extract
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Extract
<hw>Ex*tract"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Extracted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Extracting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>extractus</ets>, p.
p. of <ets>extrahere</ets> to extract; <ets>ex</ets> out +
<ets>trahere</ets> to draw. See <er>Trace</er>, and cf.
<er>Estreat</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw out or forth; to pull
out; to remove forcibly from a fixed position, as by traction or
suction, etc.; <as>as, to <ex>extract</ex> a tooth from its socket, a
stump from the earth, a splinter from the finger</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bee⟦br⟧
Sits on the bloom <qex>extracting</qex> liquid sweet.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To withdraw by expression, distillation, or other
mechanical or chemical process; <as>as, to <ex>extract</ex> an
essence</as>. Cf. <er>Abstract</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, 6.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sunbeams may be <qex>extracted</qex> from cucumbers, but the
process is tedious.</q>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To take by selection; to choose out; to cite or
quote, as a passage from a book.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <qex>extracted</qex> out of that pamphlet a few notorious
falsehoods.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To extract the root</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>to
ascertain the root of a number or quantity.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extract</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Extract
<hw>Ex"tract`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That
which is extracted or drawn out.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A portion of a book or document, separately
transcribed; a citation; a quotation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A decoction, solution, or infusion made by
dissolving out from any substance that which gives it its essential and
characteristic virtue; essence; <as>as, <ex>extract</ex> of beef;
<ex>extract</ex> of dandelion</as>; also, any substance so extracted,
and characteristic of that from which it is obtained; <as>as, quinine is
the most important <ex>extract</ex> of Peruvian bark</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A solid preparation obtained by
evaporating a solution of a drug, etc., or the fresh juice of a plant;
-- distinguished from an <xex>abstract</xex>. See <er>Abstract</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld> <def>A peculiar principle once
erroneously supposed to form the basis of all vegetable extracts; --
called also the <altname>extractive principle</altname>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Extraction; descent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>A draught or copy of writing;
certified copy of the proceedings in an action and the judgement
therein, with an order for execution.</def>
<rj><au>Tomlins.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fluid extract</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a
concentrated liquid preparation, containing a definite proportion of the
active principles of a medicinal substance. At present a fluid gram of
extract should represent a gram of the crude drug.</cd></cs></p>

<p><ent>Extractible</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Extractable</ent>⟦br⟧
